<h1>Problem 853 - 2020 IMOSL, N7, N</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 9</h2>
<p>Let \(\mathcal{S}\) be a set consisting of \(n \ge 3\) positive integers, none of which is a sum of two other distinct members of \(\mathcal{S}\). Prove that the elements of \(\mathcal{S}\) may be ordered as \(a_1, a_2, \dots, a_n\) so that \(a_i\) does not divide \(a_{i - 1} + a_{i + 1}\) for all \(i = 2, 3, \dots, n - 1\).</p>
